Matthis and Rafe picked through the woods. Crickets added their rhythm to the clicks of insects or sprites. Rafe held up a hand and waved Matthis to a tree. Matthis looked closely where Rafe pointed. A cluster of tiny human shapes gathered around a wound in the tree bark. These little people had black, shiny skin and reminded Matthis of ants, but with twiggy little arms and legs. Their hands and feet ended in a strong pair of pincer-like toes that gripped the bark. Their tiny tongues lapped the tree sap without much movement of their hairless heads. Several of the ant-like creatures trundled over one another to make their way to the sap. They admired the way they seemed to melt into the tree bark. Without a word, they continued toward Coalridge.

"So," said Matthis into the trees, "wizards don't sleep for only two hours a night."

"Also, when was the last time you ate, Matthis?"

Matthis nodded. The last meal he had eaten was days ago. Elspeth's bread. They found a wide thicket of bramble bushes and circled around it. Matthis tapped Rafe's shoulder and pointed up at the trees. A pair of eyes stared down at them, frozen in place. A pair of black ears poked above its furry head. A sleek tail hung behind it. The fox followed their movements without a stir of branches or any sudden motion.

When they cleared the brambles, Rafe stopped. "Can you feel people's emotions, yet? The way they ..." He held his hand in the air as though he expected to pull a word from it. "The way they sustain you?"

Matthis thought about the day he had touched the wizard. The mob's anger had washed over him like icy rain. He thought of Elspeth's woodpile. He remembered the softness of her cheek on his thumb. At the Miner's Guild house, he had almost felt Mercy's triumphant smile better than he saw it. 

Matthis grunted. "Wizard's don't do that either."

The trees thinned. Rooftops huddled together on one side of the village. From here, they could see the glint of moonlight on the Pit Bell. 

"People listen to you," said Matthis, "more than they listen to others."

Rafe nodded. "With practice, your magic will do the same."

Matthis sucked a long, deep breath. The air smelled fresh. Pine, oak, rain. He remembered the book, and the man with his hands raised and thousands kneeling before him. They squeezed between two buildings. Water dripped onto Matthis' forehead from the roof. They emerged onto a packed dirt road and walked down its center together. The scent of the air changed, and they stepped over a pile of horse manure.

"You've kept this a secret for a long time." Matthis's soft voice echoed off the timber walls.

"... Yes." Rafe tipped his head back and let out a long breath. Matthis saw it turn to white fog.

When they reached the center of the village square, they faced each other. The mountains hid half the moon. They heard only crickets. They shook hands. Matthis turned toward the gallows. Rafe watched him for a moment and turned his own way.

Matthis found the wizard in exactly the same spot he had left it. Its feet bones had sunk into the dirt. It stood in a shallow puddle of mud. Its sockets stared at the gibbets. Matthis stood beside the wizard. With the wizard's feet partially sunk in the ground, they stood about the same height now.

Matthis stood in front of the wizard. It didn't move. He held his hand up, inches from its chest. He swallowed and lowered his hand.

He squared his shoulders. "What," he said, "do you want?"

The wizard did not moan. It looked at him.